Ok
I like it

There's no denying that this effect isn't great on it's own. If you are getting attacked for a lot this turn, it's pretty close to a defend, which will happen a lot. If you aren't getting attacked this turn, it is pretty nice that you can use it to bank "block" in the form of temp hp for a later turn, which helps to mitigate the RNG of bad draws. However, you will often still want to play scaling or frontloaded damage effects on those off turns anyways, and there isn't always room to fit in a low impact card like this. Where it becomes more interesting is in a deck featuring several call cards (mainly protecting, though raging is a reasonable pickup if you haven't found AOE yet, while reptomancer and torch head are very good, but hard to find and won't come until very late in the run). The nature of call effects are inherently very feast or famine, and having a way to turn those back on in an emergency can be very impactful in case something went wrong. Even if you haven't lost your temp hp yet, just being able to bank a little bit more can still be useful to keep the snowball rolling. 

The thing is, I don't think call heavy decks come up very often for collector (since the best card is rare, and 2 of the other really good options are act 3 exclusives that are also somewhat hard to find). On top of that, torchbearer is abysmal in act 1, and really inefficient in act 2, costing you against all of the elites there except for lagavulin. You probably shouldn't be adding this to your deck until late act 3 if you find yourself having multiple protecting calls, torch heads, or reptomancers. I could see including one in act 2 if you were relying on raging call for your AOE and already had a protecting call as well, but it would be sketchy. If for some reason calls are one of your only scaling tools for the act 3 and 4 boss gauntlet, then this card definitely would go up in value.

Let's talk about the upgrade, because it's very odd. It essentially allows it to perform the trick of putting your calls back online multiple times in one fight, and also lets it stick around for a second cycle if you play it before any calls to build up a buffer of temp hp. It's really situational, and an extremely low priority most of the time. However, if you were in that call heavy deck, and really needed to make sure you had a way to get them back up, it becomes a very valuable upgrade to keep those valuable buffs online in case of emergency. I don't think you ever want to find yourself in the position where upgrading this is correct, but I do think that there are times where it might be the most important upgrade in your deck to survive the late game.

Notably quite good with runic pyramid, allowing you to use it on off turns more easily, and to hold onto it for the moment when your calls are taken offline. In theory, you could try to stockpile large quantities of temp hp with multiple copies and a stange spoon, but that's not a great plan (strange spoon is also generally pretty awkward for collector). I feel like you could buff this quite safely by raising the temp hp gained from the card to 8, or change to upgrade to a more traditional +3. Retain would also be a pretty cool upgrade, letting it do its job more consistently.
